        <p> As Steffi had already reported, we drove a little in the sand last night. 
		   That was another perfect example, it is not known for faith.
		   At work, I regularly preach that you check your assumptions and make you measurable before you put something into practice, but on vacation I don't stick to it myself.
		   This time it went wrong. 
		   My assumption was that our rental mobile has a front wheel drive. 
		   So it shouldn't be a problem if I put the rear wheels a little on sand.
		   As long as the front wheels are still on firm surfaces, we shouldn't have any problems.
		   Well, wrongly thought! This car has a rear -wheel drive and as soon as I only begin the wheels on the sand, we drove!
		   What does that tell us again: do not accept, but prove assumptions! </p>
		<p> Since I have never stuck with a vehicle, let alone made me a head, of course I didn't have the shimmer in such cases.
			Where is my brother, the off -road fan, when you need him.
			But since we were at a campsite and there were many other campers in sight, after the first failed attempt, I decided to wait for the next morning and not make it worse. </p>
